description:
Does AMD's RX 9070 XT slay the Nvidia RTX 5070 Ti? It certainly should do on paper, but the truth is a little more complex. Join our resident hardware overlord Dave James in this special episode of Critical Rig where we pitch the two mid-range GPUs into a head-to-head battle. Performance, pricing and value for money all factor in our detailing breakdown. So before you take the plunge and get one for yourself, listen to Dave's expert advice

0:00 - Intro
01:09 - Specs
02:52 - Price
04:45 - Performance
07:26 - Overclocking
08:46 - Verdict

comments.text:
@Yanaro-pi8pt but it's an illusion sometimes. 

Sure, the FPS counter goes up, congratulations! But the fluidity from those FPS goes away the moment you start to feel input lag, and the advantage those FPS give goes away the moment your image feels blurry and looks like it's been  smeared by vaseline due to artifacts.

It's only something to take into consideration if:

1. You already have a stable FPS counter above 60, in which case, depending on the game, you already have a good enough framerate.

2. You are playing a slow paced game that isn't prone to artifacting, in which case you didn't need the extra FPS that much anyway.

3. You are using something like path tracing and REALLY need those extra FPS, so you're willing to suffer the negatives to enjoy the positives.

4. Your game runs so badly natively that you are in dire need of upscaling because your GPU is too weak, in which case these GPUs don't enter the conversation.

But I can assure you must people don't do that evaluation, they've just been tricked to think that more FPS equals more fluidity and a better experience, even when it might be affecting their experience instead.
